Garfield Heights City Schools
November 14, 2018 at 9:27 AM ¬∑

Fifth grade student leaders from Elmwood Elementary School participated in a very meaningful ceremony which took place earlier in the week at Jennings Home as part of their annual Veteran‚Äôs Day celebration. Integrally involved with the ceremony itself, these Elmwood students, known as ‚Äúambassadors,‚Äù carried flags representing the various branches of the armed forces and hoisted them during the flag raising ceremony at the pole in front of the Jennings Home campus. From there, each fifth grade student had the opportunity to read aloud a special and personally-written statement of gratitude expressing their appreciation for the sacrifices of the men and women who were veterans in the audience.

In total, nearly 200 people participated in this ceremony and the Elmwood student ambassadors did a fantastic job of representing the Garfield Heights City Schools. Thank you to Ms. Jen Huncharek for her leadership of the student group and to Jennings Home for allowing our students to contribute to this yearly patriotic and solemn ceremony.

shared_text:
Garfield Heights Police Department - Ohio
October 29, 2018 at 9:18 AM ¬∑

As cold temperatures approach, we STRONGLY urge residents not to leave their vehicles unattended and unsecured while warming them up. Last winter we had numerous vehicles taken out of driveways while they were left running. Exhaust fumes in cold temperatures make these cars easy targets to spot.

Suspects are generally wondering the streets looking up driveways. The thefts happen within minutes of owners going back inside their houses. Several thieves were arrested last winter but no doubt they, or their associates, will be out again this winter.

DO NOT leave your vehicle running unless it can be secured by a secondary means (remote start, a second key, etc.) Also, please report ANY suspicious persons whom appear to be wandering on side streets with no apparent agenda.

Please share this message with any and all residents. This is a preventable problem and with cooperation from everyone it can be all but eliminated from our city. Thank you.

Barb Stapleton‚ÄéGarfield Heights Family Resource Center
September 30, 2014 at 8:56 PM ¬∑

If you have a friend or family member living with addiction support is available for you. Join us every Tuesday 7-8pm at The Family Resource Center located in the Garfield Heights Civic Center at 5407 Turney Road.

We have a great group of people that come and share their stories, good and bad. Some are family members, friends and some are recovering addicts or alcoholics who have amazing stories and suggestions. Sometimes we all need to vent, that's what we are here for. We to offer the support we all need just to make it through. Some come every week, others once a month or as needed.

shared_text:
Mothers Against DOPE, Drugs Overtaking People Everywhere
May 19, 2013 at 11:04 PM ¬∑

TODAY I WILL LOVE ME
For many years I have worn the face of sadness. I pushed all my needs to the back of the line. Along the way, I lost my own identity because I was always more focused on taking care of everyone else but me.
Life was passing me by because I was allowing it to.
My loved one‚Äôs addiction was controlling everything in my life‚Ä¶.because I was letting it.
My mind was no longer able to comprehend happiness. The hours of my life seemed so very unimportant.
When I looked in the mirror and in shock did not recognize who was looking back at me, it was my wakeup call.
The day came when I finally had enough!
NO more hiding from the truth.
NO more letting myself come last.
NO more feeling so used up every day!
Today and everyday from now on, I WILL make time for me!
I WILL put myself first.
I WILL love me today!

post_text: Even though Christmastime is supposed to be one the greatest and most festive days of the year, for many different reasons it's often very difficult for a lot of people to get through. Remember that Christmas is only a single day of the year and you can undoubtedly get through it. Helping someone is one way to feel better and at the same time, make someone else feel better too! Celebrate yourself and focus on the good in your life. A new year and a new start are right around the corner. . . .Warmest thoughts and best wishes for a happy, healthy, New Year!

post_text:
What Are the Common Misconceptions About Prescription Drug Abuse?

There is a reason that prescription drugs are intended to be taken under the direction of a doctor: if used improperly they can be dangerous. Teens are making the decision to abuse prescription medicines based on misinformation. In fact, many people think abusing prescription drugs is safer than abusing illicit drugs. As the facts will tell you, prescription drugs can have dangerous short-and long-term health consequences when used incorrectly or by someone other than whom they were intended.
What Is Prescription Drug Abuse?

Prescription drug abuse is when someone takes a medication that was prescribed for someone else or takes their own prescription in a manner or dosage other than what was prescribed. Abuse can include taking a friend's or relative's prescription to get high, to treat pain, or because you think it will help with studying.

IF YOU NEED A TREATMENT REFERRAL CALL 216-475-1103
